paragraphs.title: Test Time Series Extraction - Election Fraud Discussion
paragraphs.text:
// This is the Trump Election Fraud Discussion example from the book - to test we can extract timeseries from the GCAM using spark sql. I've put it into a val, so we can share the file glob
// with the rest of the notebook. 

val electionFraudTest = sqlContext.sql("""
-- for urls containing "trump" build a 15min election fraud sentiment time series chart
select  
  a.V21Date
, a.Series
, Sum(a.Sum_Normalised_Measure) as Sum_Normalised_Measure
from (
    select 
    partitionkey
    , V21Date
    , regexp_replace(z.Series, "\\.", "_") as Series
    , sum(coalesce(z.Measure, 0) / coalesce (z.WordCount, 1)) as Sum_Normalised_Measure
    -- ,V2DocId
    from
    (
        select
            --  GkgRecordID
        V21Date
        , cast(cast(round(rand(10) *1000,0) as INT) as string) as partitionkey
        , norm_array[0] as wc_norm_series
        , norm_array[1] as WordCount
        , ts_array[0] as Series
        , ts_array[1] as Measure
        from 
        (
            select
                --  GkgRecordID
              V21Date
            , split(wc_row, ":")     as norm_array                                                                      -- split the wc row into the name and value pair
            , split(gcam_array, ":") as ts_array                                                                        -- split the other gcam rows into name and value pairs
            from
                (
                select 
                  --GkgRecordID
                  V21Date                                                                                               -- grab date
                , gcam_row[0] as wc_row                                                                                 -- select out the first array entry to access wc (word count)
                , explode(gcam_row) as gcam_array                                                                       -- explode gcam array to rows
                from
                    (
                     select
                            -- GkgRecordID 
                            from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(V21Date, "yyyyMMddHHmmss"), 'YYYY-MM-dd-HH-mm') as V21Date     -- I use this to reformat the dates, so we can plot timeseries later
                        ,   split(V2GCAM, ",")  as gcam_row                                                             -- split gcam into an array
                        from PreRawData
                        where length(V2GCAM) >20
                        and V2DocId like '%trump%'
                    ) w  
                    where gcam_row[0] is not null -- like '%wc%' OR gcam_row[0] like '%c18.134:%'
                ) x
                
        ) y
        where size(norm_array) = 2 and size(ts_array) = 2           -- !! this line is to avoid any bad arrays that arrive
    ) z
    where z.Series <> "wc" and z.Series = 'c18.134'                 -- c18.140 is "ELECTION",  c18.134 is "ELECTION_FRAUD"
    group by z.partitionkey, z.V21Date, z.Series
) a
group by a.V21Date, a.Series
""")

electionFraudTest.registerTempTable("electionFraudTest")

paragraphs.title: Explore Normalised BREXIT GCAM Time Series - final reusable code
paragraphs.text:
//  Extracting Normalised Timeseries data from GCAM
//
//  This is a complex query. Don't be worried. It will unfold the gkg GCAM records from there nested format into a timeseries format.
//  It looks complex simply because it nests multiple subqueries together to create an entire processing pipeline for reading our GCAM data in one pass.
//  You can read this SQL from the middle (outside right) inward, through the indentations to the left.
//
//  Note you can copy the sql out in subquery sized parts, to run subqueries individually, in a step by step way to see the data transformations through the pipeline.
//  The order of precedence is always backwards. The first select defines the last transformation, the subquery before it precedes it and so forth.
//
//  In idiomatic scala, we alternatively use the functions EXPLODE and to SPLIT to unpick those nested arrays. Notice here - I am doing this too, but in SQL.
//  I also apply some logic to fields inside of arrays using array indexing notation like: field[1] 
//  If you are an old hand at SQL on tranditional databases, these new ways of processing arrays within SQL, are a powerful extension you should learn.
//  If you are new to SQL, and prefer other syntax, remember that this processing pipeline is highly portable. 
//  Run it from pyspark, Run it from R, Run it from scala ... 

// Always remember when writing SQL. Formatting it to be readable is the key to success. ALWAYS code sql with style. Indent, align aliass, use these visual aids to help troubleshoot.
// Include comments in your sql, it is easy and helpful when you revisit the code later. A double dash is a comment marker to the end of the line.


val ExtractGcam = sqlContext.sql("""
select                                                          -- #### this sums up the metrics over our final groups
  a.V21Date
, a.Series
, a.SourceLanguage
, a.FIPS104Country
, Sum(a.Sum_Normalised_Measure) as Sum_Normalised_Measure
from (
    select                                                      -- #### clean up series names, country codes, and calculate our metrics. Use defaults for nulls via coalesce!
    z.partitionkey
    , z.V21Date
    , regexp_replace(z.Series, "\\.", "_")                      as Series                        -- periods in field names isn't great naming, we'll swap them for underscores.
    , z.SourceLanguage
    , substr(z.FIPS104Country, 1, 2)                            as FIPS104Country
    , sum(coalesce(z.Measure, 0) / coalesce (z.WordCount, 1))   as Sum_Normalised_Measure         --coalesce in sql means swap nulls for a default value
    from
    (
        select                                                   -- #### create a pre-partitioning key to fragment very large groups, helps subdivide hotspots. Pull array values into final columns.
            --  GkgRecordID
        y.V21Date
        , cast(cast(round(rand(10) *10000,0) as INT) as string) as partitionkey
        , y.norm_array[0] as wc_norm_series
        , y.norm_array[1] as WordCount
        , y.ts_array[0]   as Series                             -- and here you see we can reference and select out the previously "split" data by the array index numbers.
        , y.ts_array[1]   as Measure                            -- and here you see we can reference and select out the previously "split" data by the array index numbers.
        , y.SourceLanguage
        , y.FIPS104Country
        from 
        (
            select                                              -- #### split the nested records by delimeter into fields. one array per row, indexed from 1 .. n, select location, cleanse lang code field.
            -- x.GkgRecordID                                    -- removed on this pass
              x.V21Date
            , split(x.wc_row, ":")                              as norm_array
            , split(x.gcam_array, ":")                          as ts_array       -- again, how we have exploded the data, we can split it again, to get the internal fields out of these rows
            , x.Location_Array[3]                               as FIPS104Country
            , regexp_replace(x.SourceLanguage, "srclc:", "")    as SourceLanguage
            from
                (
                    select                                      -- #### create a pre-partitioning key to fragment very large groups, helps subdivide hotspots. Pull array values into final columns.
                      --GkgRecordID                             -- removed on this pass.
                      w.V21Date
                    , w.gcam_row[0]                             as wc_row
                    , explode(w.gcam_row)                       as gcam_array        -- note you can only "explode" arrays, which are created using "split" in the subquery below
                    , split(w.Location, "#")                    as Location_Array
                    , coalesce(w.SourceLanguage, "srclc:eng")   as SourceLanguage
                    from
                        (
                         select
                                -- GkgRecordID                             -- removed 
                                from_unixtime(unix_timestamp(V21Date, "yyyyMMddHHmmss"), 'YYYY-MM-dd-HH') as V21Date
                            ,   split(V2GCAM, ",")                         as gcam_row                                  -- this line creates an array of rows
                            ,   regexp_replace(V1Locations, ";.*$", "")    as Location                                  -- this line using string regex to only take data to the first delimiter
                            ,   regexp_replace(V21TransInfo, ";.*$", "")   as SourceLanguage                            -- ditto
                            from 
                                PreRawData
                            where 
                                length(V2GCAM) > 20                                                                     -- this line checks there's actually data in V2GCAM
                                and V2GCAM like "%,%"                                                                   -- and this one that it has the delimiters, and hopefully real data
                            --- ###########################################                            
                            and V2DocId like '%brexit%'                         --< add your topic of enquiry here to filter, here I am filtering on URLs >--
                            --- ###########################################
                        ) w 
                        where 
                            gcam_row[0] like '%wc%' 
                        OR  gcam_row[0] like 'c%'
                        AND size(gcam_row) = 1                                -- !! this line checks the array size has at least a size of 1. Avoids us reading empty arrays. 
                ) x
                where x.wc_row like "%:%" and x.gcam_array like "%:%"
                
        ) y where size(norm_array) = 2 and size(ts_array) = 2                 -- !! this line is to avoid negative array index errors. I had an odd error when exploring
    ) z
    where z.Series <> "wc"  
    
    -- ### I have removed all where clauses below, to PICK UP EVERYTHING     #### but feel free to uncomment it and to refocus on particular series.
    -- ### to recreate the time series chart in the book, uncomment it.
    --    and 
    --    -- select out the 4 examples from the book
    --    (   z.Series = 'c18.134' -- Election Fraud   
    --     or z.Series = 'c18.101' -- Immigration
    --     or z.Series = 'c18.100' -- Democracy
    --     or z.Series = 'c18.140' -- Election
    --    )  
    
    group by 
      z.partitionkey     -- readers: see here how I pre-aggregate using a subparitioning key to cope with hotspots a little better? The GROUP BY below doesn't have this. 
    , z.V21Date
    , z.Series
    , z.FIPS104Country
    , z.SourceLanguage
) a
group by a.V21Date, a.Series, a.FIPS104Country, a.SourceLanguage
""")

ExtractGcam.registerTempTable("ExtractGcam")

//ExtractGcam.cache()
//ExtractGcam.persist(StorageLevel.MEMORY_AND_DISK_SER).count()
//ExtractGcam.printSchema()
//ExtractGcam.show(5, false)

val FixedExtractGcam = sqlContext.sql("""
select 
V21Date
, Series
, CASE                                  -- I notice quite late, that the english files aren't encoding the language field as I thought. Catch the error and correct it here.
    when LangLen = 0 then "eng"
    when LangLen > 0 then SourceLanguage
  END
  as SourceLanguage
, FIPS104Country
, Sum_Normalised_Measure
from
(
    select *, length(SourceLanguage) as LangLen     -- because the SourceLanguage fields are empty rather than null, we can use field length to then use a CASE above to correct that.
    from BrexitTimeSeries
    -- where v21Date like "2016-2%"

) a
""")
